[While there is much discussion about the passengers on the ship, the discussions re: the crew have been limited. To date there have been at least 10 cases confirmed among crew on the ship, individuals who sleep in dormitory-like quarters with multiple individuals in the same room. Many of these individuals have been interfacing with the passengers, potentially serving as 2-way transmission streams if use of PPE (personal protective equipment) isn't completely observed. Interestingly there have not been reports of additional cases confirmed in the past 24 hours, but is this a function of the volume of specimens tested, or does it reflect no newly confirmed cases?

As for the passengers with confirmed COVID-19, an age distribution of the passengers was provided by ProMED-mail Rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka from media reports in Japanese:
20-29: 10
30-39: 7
40-49: 7
50-59: 20
60-69: 50
70-79: 73
80-89: 49
90-99: 2

79.8% are 60 years of age or older. - Mod.MPP]

